esis is about the place of employment in young adult lives. It seeks to capture distinctive elements of the contemporary moment for this generation in two European cities, Bristol and Gothenburg, at the beginning of the twenty-first century. The cities were chosen as research sites because they exemplify post-industrial, ?globalizing cities? in advanced capitalist societies. Although processes of globalization are thought to compromise the distinctive features of cities, this study counters these claims and explores how simultaneously global and local trends are played out in young adult lives. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>It achieves this through its focus on three substantive themes in the sociology of work and sociology of youth: orientations to work and life, processes of individualization, and patterns of transition to adulthood in Europe. This thesis draws on biographical interviews carried out with 48 employed young adults (aged 20-35) living in Bristol and Gothenburg in 2000/03 to address these themes. Adopting an innovative approach to the analysis of young adult biographies, this study explores the meanings invested in life transitions between employment, unemployment, education, having children and travel. The narrative approach links the strategies young adults use to make sense out of these discontinuities with their differential employment outcomes.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2006-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>28406</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">PTA-026-27-1229</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-B